Date: Sat 21 Jul 2001 14:26:49 -0400
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Sun Star Wed 4 Jul 2001 [edited
<http://www.sunstar.com.ph/lycos/07-04-2001/story4.html>

Increase in Dengue Fever Cases Reported in Philippines (Benguet)
----------------------------------------------------------------
BAGUIO: At least 334 individuals in Benguet province were reported to
be suffering from dengue fever even as regional hospitals reported
having admitted 60 new cases of the disease from the city. But the
Department of Health-Cordillera (DOH-CAR) is not yet inclined to
declare an epidemic at this time. Of the 334 dengue cases in Benguet,
232 were reported from the town of Bokod; the remaining 102 were from
the mining town of Mankayan.
No deaths were reported, but numbers of dengue cases are expected to
increase in the coming days, according to Bony Bengwayan, information
officer of the DOH-CAR. In spite of these confirmed cases, the DOH-CAR
has yet to concede that the reported dengue fever cases in Benguet and
Baguio are enough to declare a dengue outbreak in these areas. There
is a standing policy of DOH-CAR that an outbreak will be declared if
at least 10 individuals or more from one barangay are suffering from a
common disease.
Nevertheless, Bengwayan told the Sun Star that a 7-man team from the
Epidemiology Division of DOH-CAR with augmentation from DOH central
office was immediately dispatched to Bokod and Mankayan to gather
blood samples from the suspected dengue patients and were expected to
arrive in Baguio yesterday.
Bengwayan claimed that the upward trend in the number of dengue cases
had been anticipated by the health department, saying that [the
frequency of dengue cases is cyclic; cases increase every 2 or 3
years. "As of now I cannot tell you that the regional office will
declare a dengue outbreak in Benguet and Baguio city," Bengwayan said.
But last Monday, City Health Officer Florence Reyes had hinted at a
possible declaration of a dengue outbreak in the city. This developed
even as Reyes shared Benwayan's belief that the upward trend of dengue
cases was expected.
An initial report gathered by the DOH-CAR revealed that Barangays
Campo Filipino, Lucban, Aurora Hil, City Camp, and Scout Barrio are
infested with _Aedes aegypti_, the dengue fever [vector.
[Byline: Harley Palangchao
