Source: Sun Star Network, Sun 22 Jul 2001 [edited
<http://www.sunstar.com.ph/pooled_reports/07222001-3.html>

Philippines Update: Cebu Accounts for 25% of Dengue Cases
---------------------------------------------------------
CEBU: Cebu now accounts for 25 percent of dengue cases in the country.
As a result, the Department of Health (DOH) has placed the province on
high-level alert. The number of local children afflicted by the
disease has also risen considerably since May, surpassing numbers of
cases in the National Capital Region (NCR). Health Secretary Manuel
Dayrit said Cebu has now topped NCR with a record of 1300 dengue cases
over the latter's 1200. The nationwide total is 5000.
As of Fri 20 Jul 2001, fatalities from the disease have reached 50.
Dayrit said he has ordered DOH 7 to strengthen the information drive
on preventing contracting the disease and to continue with the fogging
operation. He said the seriously affected areas are Capitol, Nivel
Hills, Barangays Apas and Sitio Banawa, Guadalupe in Cebu city;
Barangay Lawaan in Minglanilla town; Toledo city; and Yati, Liloan. In
the first quarter of this year [2001, at least 26 cases of dengue
fever were reported in Barangay Guadalupe, according to a City Health
Department report. The number was the highest among Cebu city's 80
barangays. The dengue virus is transmitted by the _Aedes aegypti_
mosquito. Symptoms of the disease such as fever, berry-like skin rash,
and swollen glands develop within 3 to 15 days. Internal bleeding may
also develop if the patient is not quickly treated. The epidemic
occurs during the wet season, when mosquitoes have ample breeding
grounds.
Health officials earlier said the key to controlling dengue is the
elimination of the mosquitoes' breeding sites. The disease-carrying
mosquito bites between 4:30 and 8:30 a.m. and between 4:30 and 8:30
p.m. It breeds in stagnant water outside the house, such as in
gutters, tires, and tin cans. [Stagnant generally carries the
meaning of polluted; _Aedes aegypti_ needs clean water that is still,
not flowing - Mod.JW
But regular cleaning should also be done indoors, as mosquito eggs
also thrive in water in a flower vase, collected bottles, and radiator
pads of refrigerators. Collected water in drums and other containers
should always be covered.
In the Cordillera Administrative Region, dengue cases represented a
243 percent increase from the 127 cases recorded this year, compared
to only 37 cases last year. As this situation developed, the DOH-CAR
is recommending that local health units strengthen their information
and education campaign regarding prevention and control of these
diseases.
