Date: Sat 21 Jul 2001 11:11:22 +0100
From: Michael Adey-Jones
Source: Phuket Gazette, 15-31 Jul 2001 [edited

Increase in Dengue Fever Cases in Phuket, Thailand
--------------------------------------------------
PHUKET: The Phuket Health Office (PHO) has issued its second dengue
fever warning in less than a month. On 12 Jun 2001, the PHO reported
that 55 cases of dengue fever had been recorded since the beginning of
the year. By 5 Jul 2001, it announced that the figure had risen to 75.
Dr. Boonrieng Chuchaisaengrat, chief of the PHO, told the Gazette, "At
this time of year, from June to August, there is a (greater) risk,
everywhere in Thailand, of getting dengue fever. In Phuket, we have
been able to control the spread of the disease and have yet to have a
fatality from it." Dr. Boonrieng said that the PHO will continue its
campaign to encourage people to rid their surroundings of conditions
in which mosquitoes can breed, especially pools of stagnant water.
[Stagnant generally carries the meaning of polluted; _Aedes aegypti_
needs clean water that is still, not flowing - Mod.JW
So far this year, dengue fever has claimed 79 lives in Thailand.
--
Michael Adey-Jones
Chairman
Mental Health Care Group, UK
